---
import VizPlaceholder from '../../VizPlaceholder.astro';

const plumbing = [
  {
    num: '01',
    title: 'Fetch and branch',
    body: 'Pull the second repo and get it onto the right branch.',
  },
  {
    num: '02',
    title: 'Set up worktrees',
    body: 'So agents work in each repo independently, without stepping on each other.',
  },
  {
    num: '03',
    title: 'Route context by hand',
    body: 'CLAUDE.md files, custom scripts, copied-in markdown, so each agent knows what the other is doing.',
  },
  {
    num: '04',
    title: 'Land the PRs together',
    body: 'Push the coordinated PRs so they land together instead of breaking each other.',
  },
];
---

<section
  id="barrier"
  class="border-y border-neutral-900 bg-neutral-900/40 px-6 py-20 md:py-28"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <h2
        class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
      >
        The same barrier, again
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
        At that new altitude you hit the exact stitching problem from before, one
        level up. You are now looking at the backend repo and the frontend repo
        at once, but the harness is local to each. To make one agent work across
        both, you become the plumbing. Concretely, today, with just a harness:
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 grid items-center gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="lg:order-first">
        <VizPlaceholder label="CrossRepoBeforeAfter island" ratio="aspect-[16/10]" />
      </div>

      <ol>
        {
          plumbing.map((step, i) => (
            <li class="flex gap-4">
              <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
                <span class="flex h-9 w-9 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full border border-neutral-700 bg-neutral-950 font-mono text-xs text-accent">
                  {step.num}
                </span>
                {i < plumbing.length - 1 && (
                  <span class="my-1 w-px flex-1 bg-neutral-800" />
                )}
              </div>
              <div class="pb-8 last:pb-0">
                <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-neutral-100">
                  {step.title}
                </h3>
                <p class="mt-1 text-base leading-relaxed text-neutral-400">
                  {step.body}
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
      <p>
        And that is only the first problem. The second one is quieter and worse.
        You spent a session with an agent working through a tricky piece of the
        system, and a lot of reasoning went into it: why this approach, what you
        ruled out, where the sharp edges are. <mark>Where does that go?</mark>
        The session log is a file on your machine. In a month, when a bug report
        lands on exactly that feature, you want to pull that reasoning back, and
        there is nowhere it lives that you or anyone else can reach.
      </p>
    </div>

    <figure class="mx-auto mt-16 max-w-3xl border-t border-neutral-800 pt-10 text-center">
      <p class="text-lg text-neutral-400">
        Everyone hits these two problems right now, cross-repo plumbing and
        session knowledge with nowhere to live.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-2xl font-medium leading-snug text-neutral-100 sm:text-3xl">
        That is the <span class="text-accent">harness gap</span>.
      </p>
    </figure>
  </div>
</section>
